{"cursor":"48672","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox person |name = Pliny the Elder or Gaius Plinius Secundus |image =\nplinyelder.jpg |imagesize = 178px |caption = Pliny the Elder: an imaginative 19th-\ncentury portrait. No contemporary depiction of Pliny has survived. |birth_date =\nAD 23 |birth_place = Como, Italy |death_date = |death_place = Stabiae, near\nPompei, Italy |occupation = Lawyer, author, |spouse = None |parents = Celer and\nMarcella |children = None |weight = Corpulent in later life |citizenship = Roman\n|relations = Sister (Plinia), |box_width = 270px |residence = Rome, provincial\nlocations, Misenum |death_cause = Died in the eruption that destroyed Pompeii\n|body_discovered= By friends, under the pumice |education = Rhetoric, grammar\n|notable works = Natural History }}\n\n\n'Gaius Plinius Secundus' (AD 23 â August 25, AD 79), better known as 'Pliny the\nElder', was a Roman author, naturalist, and natural philosopher, as well as\nnaval and army commander of the early Roman Empire, and personal friend of the\nemperor Vespasian. Spending most of his spare time studying, writing or\ninvestigating natural and geographic phenomena in the field, he wrote an\nencyclopedic work, [[Natural History (Pliny)|Naturalis Historia]], which became\na model for all such works written subsequently. Pliny the Younger, his nephew,\nwrote of him in a letter to the historian Tacitus:  :For my part I\ndeem those blessed to whom, by favour of the gods, it has been granted either to\ndo what is worth writing of, or to write what is worth reading; above measure\nblessed those on whom both gifts have been conferred. In the latter number will\nbe my uncle, by virtue of his own and of your compositions.\n Pliny is referring to the fact that Tacitus relied on his uncle's\nnow missing work on the History of the German Wars. Pliny the Elder died on\nAugust 25, 79 AD, while attempting the rescue by ship of a friend and his family\nfrom the eruption of